# Project rules

- When creating plans if a lib is needed, try to check if it is in the conan repo. If it is, say it with a warning to add it, since the user has the conan extension installed. If it doesn't, ask the user to install it under the vendor folder.
- Ensures that when reading files, it avoids the TOCTOU vulnerability. So it needs to do atomic operations. This could mean opening a file in appended mode, or reading and writing in a single operation. And then validating the file contents, so we know it is a trusted file.

## File naming convention (DOD C++)

Every header must fit exactly one of these five categories:

- `*Types.h` — data only: structs, enums, POD handles. No methods. Namespace = module root (`DotEngine`, `DotData`).
- `*System.h` / `*System.cpp` — free functions that operate on types. Namespace must be `DotEngine::<FileStem>` (e.g. `BufferSystem.h` → `namespace DotEngine::Renderer`).
- `*Context.h` — one aggregate state struct. File name must equal type name. No other types.
- `*Macros.h` — preprocessor defines only. No types, no namespaces.
- `<ClassName>.h` / `<ClassName>.cpp` — one class per file, file name equals class name.

Rules:
- A `*Types.h` file may group multiple related POD structs (e.g. `RenderTypes.h`, `WindowTypes.h`).
- A `*System.h` file must not define types; forward-declare them from the matching `*Types.h`.
- Never mix categories in a single file.

## Engine runtime vs editor host

**Engine Runtime** (shippable game): EngineCore, Platform, Renderer, GameInput. No Editor.

**Editor** (tool layer): DotEditor — ImGui host, `EditorContext`, panel registry. Built only when `DOT_EDITOR` is ON.

**Application host** owns composition via `ApplicationContext` (`engine`, `gameInput`, and `editor` when `DOT_EDITOR`).

```text
GLFW → Platform → EngineContext.events
                      ↓
              Application routes
                 /         \
          GameInput      Editor (DOT_EDITOR only)
```

## Module terminology

- **`EngineContext`** — runtime only (`graphics`, `window`, `events`, `running`). Lives in **EngineCore**.
- **`ApplicationContext`** — application host owns `engine`, `gameInput`, and `editor` (`DOT_EDITOR`). Stored on GLFW user pointer.
- **`Event` / `EventSystem`** — generic OS/window events in EngineCore. Platform pushes via `ApplicationContext`; consumers read from `engine.events`.
- **`DotEditor`** — editor tool layer. `EditorContext`, `EditorSystem`, `EditorEventSystem::ProcessEvents`.
- **`EditorPanelSystem`** — `RegisterPanel` only. Panel implementations live in client apps (Sandbox).
- **`UI`** — reserved for future in-game interfaces (not editor).

## Input boundaries

- **Platform** stores `ApplicationContext*` on the GLFW window and pushes `Event` to `app.engine.events`. Links `DotApplication` for the host type; never links DotEditor.
- **`GameInput`** — consumes `EventQueue` via `ProcessEvents`. Shipped in game runtime.
- **`Editor::ProcessEvents`** — consumes same queue for panel dispatch (`DOT_EDITOR` only).
- Application calls `GameInput::ProcessEvents` then `Editor::ProcessEvents`, then `Events::Clear`.

## Pure DOD principles

Default contract (unless a plan explicitly opts out):

- Data in `*Types.h` / context structs — POD only, no methods, no virtuals, no I/O
- Behavior in `*System.h` — free functions; pass explicit slices (`EngineContext&`, `EditorContext&`, `GameInputState&`)
- No thin getters that only return a field — read `ctx.field` directly
- No hidden module globals — state on context structs; Application wires slices
- Backend systems write context slices at init; consumers read fields directly
- No virtual dispatch in the frame loop
- SoA for 100+ homogeneous hot-path items; singleton subsystems stay AoS

Architecture PRs must include a **DOD compliance** note: POD vs systems added, opt-outs, and runtime vs editor layer touched.
